1 DESCRIPTION DESC~
Syntax: description
Syntax: description edit
Syntax: description format

Typing DESCRIPTION, with NO argument, or ANY argument NOT listed in the
above SYNTAX, will simply show you what your current description is.

Typing DESCRIPTION EDIT will enter you into an editor. This editor is
similar to the one you write notes in. You can write your entire
description in here with ease. To see the list of usable commands while
inside the editor, on a NEW line (Hit Return to put yourself on a new
line, if the line your on has any text on it), type    .h
and then hit RETURN.

You MUST include the PERIOD before the letter H, otherwise you'll just
enter in the letter H on your new line. Always remember, each command
you type, must ALWAYS be on a new line, otherwise it will just add what
you type, to the rest of the text on your line. For example, once you
have finished writing your description, on a NEW line, you can type .f
(then hit return), and your description will be formatted. After
each command, you will always be placed on a NEW line, so after you've
formatted your description, you will already be on a new line, and don't
need to hit return again. Then you would type: @ (and then hit return)
to exit the description editor. If you feel uncomfortable using this
editor, you can alays write up your description another way, as
described below.
 
DESCRIPTION FORMAT will wrap your description text, making it look pretty
and more professional and presentable, not to mention, legible.
 
Again, it is highly recommended that you learn how to use the description
editor. Writing descriptions using that editor can make things a lot
easier.
 
Your description is the first impression that you make on others. It is
how you appear to the outside world.  It is what people see when they
look at you (other than your condition and your equipment list).  Your
description is one of the foundations of your roleplaying. Through it, you
can get across to others many things about your character, before you even
say a word.
 
Your description is comprised of the text above the line indicating your
condition.  You must write a description by level 10, though it is
advisable to write one as soon as possible.  The process of writing a
description helps decide the characters' history.
 
When you create a character, the character begins young. For humans the
age is seventeen years old.  All other races begin at the equivalent age
for their race. At the very least, know what the character looks like and
have a rough idea of the character's background before beginning to
adventure. Remember, as the character grows and changes, you can change or
add to your character's description.
 
There are many types of descriptions.  The purely physical attributes
should be referred to in a good description (height, weight, build,
hair/eye/skin color, complexion etc).  They can include certain
characteristics of your character (a limp, a scar, a particular way of
moving, an aura of good/evil/power, etc).
 
The best descriptions combine all of these aspects by being mainly
physical, but describing the various physical aspects in ways that reveal
some of the character's underlying background, motivations, etc.
Multi-line descriptions are required, as you cannot possibly be
descriptive enough in just one line.  The syntax above should allow you to
easily write your description.
 
Descriptions should and need to be written in the 3'rd person, not first or
second, as you are not telling a personal story of your adventures.
 
A good example would be:
A silver-haired drow of very slight build is here.  He has dark,
unblemished skin that has never seen the harsh conditions of the upper
world's weather.  His pale white hair is streaked with a glistening silver
and is held back in one long sleek braid.  He wears no sword, but the
loose folds of his garments could easily have small daggers stashed away
from normal view.  A tattoo on his shoulder is a red spider with a
sinister black diamond on the body.  His golden eyes gleam brightly and
frequently search the area.
~

