0 TITLE~
The game supplies a title when your character is created and when you 
advance a level. The only way you may have your very own "special"
re-strung title, is if you prove yourself in Roleplay, that you earn it.
For example, if you wanted the title 'The Nightslayer of Palanthas', for
roleplay, we'd want to see something like, night after night you run into
the city and commit serious murders. Something to that effect. And it would
have to be something you roleplay constantly. Don't think you'll be able to
get away with acting some way one time and then beg or demand an Immortal
to give you a title. We watch everyone's roleplay and when/if an Immortal
notices that you Roleplay in that particular manner constantly, then you
shall be approached and the Immortal will give you suggestion. If you do
not like the suggestion for the title, you may then come up with your own,
however, it must be something related to your Roleplay and the Immortal's
first suggestion. If you Roleplay a Nightslayer of Palanthas, and the Imm
suggests the above mention title, but you don't like it, come up with 
something else, but something along those lines, not something out of whack
like 'The Master Dark Mage of Krynn'.
 
One other thing, although that is generally the only way to receive a title,
there is one other method, and that is becoming a Leader of a Clan. It will,
however, be a title dealing with your Clan.
 
Also, those players who reach HERO status (level 101) will get to use this
command at any time, provided an Immortal has removed their NOTITLE status
first.
~

0 WIMPY~
Syntax: wimpy
Syntax: wimpy <number>

WIMPY sets your wimpy value.  When your character takes damage that reduces
your hit points below your wimpy value, you will automatically attempt to flee.
You will only flee if your character is not in a wait state -- i.e. has not
been using combat commands like cast, trip and bash, and has not been
tripped or bash by an enemy.

WIMPY with no argument sets your wimpy value to 20% of your maximum hit points.

Some monsters are wimpy.
~

0 OPEN CLOSE LOCK UNLOCK PICK~
Syntax: open   <object|direction>
Syntax: close  <object|direction>
Syntax: lock   <object|direction>
Syntax: unlock <object|direction>
Syntax: pick   <object|direction>

- For those using the LOCK SPELL -
Syntax: cast 'lock' <object|direction>

OPEN and CLOSE open and close an object or a door.
** Note:  If opening a DOOR, remember to type the DIRECTION, not the word
{x          DOOR itself.

LOCK and UNLOCK lock and unlock a closed object or door.  You must have
the requisite key to LOCK or UNLOCK.

PICK can open a lock without having the key.  In order to PICK successfully,
you must practice the appropriate skill.
 
And for the SPELL called LOCK, it will do the same as the LOCK command, only
you are casting a spell, instead of physically doing it, and your NOT required
to have a KEY, like you would if you were to lock something physically with
the command.
~

0 DRINK EAT FILL POUR~
Syntax: drink <object>
Syntax: eat   <object>
Syntax: fill  <object>
Syntax: pour  <object> out
Syntax: pour  <object> <object>
Syntax: pour  <object> <character>

You will not experience the effects of Hunger or Thirst as a Newbie. Once
you reach level 6, that is when you will begin to experience hunger and
thirst. Watch your screen carefully, as you will be warned when you begin
to feel hungry and/or thirsty. If you let it go for too long, you WILL begin
to lose Hit Points and eventually die when your HP runs down to 0.
Starvation and Dehydration will kill you here. You will be warned when you
begin to die from either of the two. So make sure you keep plenty of water
and food with you.
 
When you are thirsty, DRINK something.

When you are hungry, EAT something.

FILL fills a drink container with water.

POUR transfers a liquid to a container, or empties one.
You can also pour from an object into something a character is holding.
~

0 BUY LIST SELL VALUE~
Syntax: buy   <object>
Syntax: list
Syntax: sell  <object>
Syntax: value <object>

BUY buys an object from a shop keeper.
When multiple items of the same name are listed, type 'buy n.item', where n
is the position of the item in a list of that name.  So if there are two
swords, buy 2.sword will buy the second. If you want to buy multiples of
an item, use an * (buy 5*pie will buy 5 pies).  These can be combined into
(for example) buy 2*2.shield, as long as the * is first.  

LIST lists the objects the shop keeper will sell you.
List <name> shows you only objects of that name.

SELL sells an object to a shop keeper.

VALUE asks the shop keeper how much he, she, or it will buy the item for.
~

0 SACRIFICE~
Syntax: sacrifice <object>

SACRIFICE offers an object to the GOD whom you worship, rewarding you with
gold. The amount of the reward depends upon the type of object your
sacrificing. SAC ALL may be used to sacrifice everything in the room
thats lying on the ground all at once.
~

0 SCROLL~
Syntax: scroll
Syntax: scroll <number>

This command changes the number of lines the mud sends you in a page (the 
default is 24 lines).  Change this to a higher number for larger screen
sizes, or to 0 to disabling paging.
~

0 BRANDISH QUAFF RECITE ZAP~
Syntax: brandish
Syntax: quaff    <potion>
Syntax: recite   <scroll> <target>
Syntax: zap      <target>
Syntax: zap

BRANDISH brandishes a magical staff.  QUAFF quaffs a magical potion (as opposed
to DRINK, which drinks mundane liquids).  RECITE recites a magical scroll; the
<target> is optional, depending on the nature of the scroll.  ZAP zaps a
magical wand at a target.  If the target is not specified, and you are fighting
someone, then that character is used for a target.

You must HOLD a wand or a staff before using BRANDISH or ZAP.

All of these commands use up their objects.  Potions and scrolls have a single
charge.  Wands and staves have multiple charges.  When a magical object has no
more charges, it will be consumed.

These commands may require an item skill to be succesful, see the help entries
on the skills scrolls, staves, and wands for more information.
~

0 CONSIDER~
Syntax: consider <character>

CONSIDER tells you what your chances are of killing a character.
Of course, it's only a rough estimate.
~

0 FOLLOW GROUP GROUPING~
Syntax: follow <character>
Syntax: group
Syntax: group <character>

FOLLOW starts you following another character.  To stop following anyone else,
just FOLLOW <yourself>.

GROUP <character> makes someone who is following you a member of your group.
Group members share experience points from kills and may use the GTELL and
SPLIT commands.  If anyone in your group is attacked, you will automatically
join the fight.

If the <character> is already a member of your group, then GROUP will
kick out the <character> from your group.  Characters can also leave your
group by using a FOLLOW command to stop following you.

GROUP with no argument shows statistics for each character in your group.

Grouping will only beneficial for experience points, if you group with players
within 10 levels of your own. A group of 2 will always gain more XP than one
would by him or herself. A group of 3 people will gain even more XP per kill
than both of those instances. Mobs do not get included in the deciding factor
as to how many experience points each person receieve. The group could have
15 charmies, but if it has only 3 players, you'll still be within that 3
person limit and will still gain a great amount of experience points.
A group of 4 or more Players, or a group with someone Outside of the 6 level
plus or minus range, will result in everyone in the group, only recieving
1 experience point per kill, no matter what your group kills.
 
Groups also have 3 different fighting positions, just like on the game,
Final Fantasy. There is a Front, Middle and Rear position. The person in
the Front, will recieve the most damage, but will also get in the most hits
which means if he/she is good, will deal the most damage. The person in the
Middle position, will recieve roughly only half of the damage (gets hit only
half the time), but will not get in as many hits as the person in the Front
will. The person in the Rear position, will not be hit at all by the Mob,
unless the Mob can cast AREA spells, in which case, will hit everyone. The
Rear position will not allow the player to physically hit the Mob, but will
allow most spells to be cast, which WILL hit the Mob. The Rear position is
usually best for Mages, where they can cast their spells and not worry about
getting beat up to easily. The Rear position is also good for those who need
to rest for a few, but not have to flee the scene. To move about in a group,
see 'help advance' and 'help backward'. Also see 'help battle tactics'.
 
If fighting a large group of Monsters, it is possible for them to advance and
attack someone in the Rear position, which in turn will place them in the
middle or front position, and they will uncontrollably be tanking.
(see 'help tanking' for a better explanation of what that is).
~

0 VISIBLE~
VISIBLE cancels your hiding and sneaking, as well as any invisibility,
making you visible again.
~

0 QUIT RENT SAVE~
Syntax: QUIT
Syntax: RENT ... not!
Syntax: SAVE

SAVE saves your character and object.  The game saves your character every
15 minutes regardless, and is the preferred method of saving.  Typing save
will block all other command for about 20 seconds, so use it sparingly.
(90+ players all typing save every 30 seconds just generated too much lag)

Some objects, such as keys and potions, may not be saved.

QUIT leaves the game.  You may QUIT anywhere.  When you re-enter the game 
you will be back in the same room.

QUIT automatically does a SAVE, so you can safely leave the game with just one
command.  Nevertheless it's a good idea to SAVE before QUIT.  If you get into
the habit of using QUIT without SAVE, and then you play some other mud that
doesn't save before quitting, you're going to regret it.

Also, there are QUIT TIMERS in this game. It is a timer that automatically
sets itself to a certain number whenever you get into a fight. The number
sets higher when you attack another player, as to give the player a
small chance to claim his/her revenge. The quit timer can only be seen by
Immortals. You can NOT quit with this timer on. You must wait it out. No
Immortal will ever tell you what your quit timer is set at, so don't ask.

There is no RENT in this mud.  Just SAVE and QUIT whenever you want to leave.
~

1 RECALL /~
Syntax: recall
{x        /

RECALL will send you back to your hometown.  After level 11, recall can
only be used by those with the 'word of recall' spell, or those who can
recite scrolls and happen to recite a scroll of recall.  RECALL costs half
of your movement points and will NOT work in certain god-forsaken rooms. 
Characters affected by a CURSE will also not be able to recall.  If you
RECALL during combat, you WILL lose experience points (more than you would
for fleeing) and there is a greater chance of failing than there is from
fleeing.  The chance is based on your recall skill, although even at 100%,
RECALL does not ensure success, so don't waste your practices on the skill. 
~

-1 SPLIT~
Syntax: SPLIT <silver> <gold>

SPLIT splits some coins  between you and all the members of your
group who are in the same room as you.  It's customary to SPLIT
the loot after a kill.  The first argument is the amount of silver
the split (0 is acceptable), and the second gold (optional).
Examples:
split 30 	--> split 30 silver
split 20 50	--> split 20 silver, 50 gold
split  0 10	--> split 10 gold
~

0 STEAL~
Syntax: STEAL coin <character>
{x        STEAL gold <character>
{x        STEAL steel <character>
{x        STEAL coins <character>
{x        STEAL <object> <character>

STEAL attempts to steal coins, or an object, from a character.
Beware, stealing from other players can earn you a Theft flag if
your caught and convicted by a Solamnic Knight.
~

0 PRACTICE~
Syntax: PRACTICE
Syntax: PRACTICE <skill|spell>

PRACTICE without an argument tells you your current ability level in all
the skills and spells available to you.  You can check this anywhere.

PRACTICE with an argument practice that skill or spell.  Your learning
percentage varies from 0% (unlearned) to a some maximum between 80% and 100%,
depending on your class.  You must be at a guild master to practice.

The higher your intelligence, the more you will learn at each practice
session.  The higher your wisdom, the more practice sessions you will
have each time you gain a level.  Unused sessions are saved until you
do use them.
 
If a spell or skill has an N/A displayed next to it, that means the spell
is not yet available to you, your not that level yet, hence it is not
usable or practicable until you reach that level.
~

0 TRAIN~
Syntax: train <str int wis dex con hp mana>

TRAIN increases one of your attributes.  When you start the game, your
character has standard attributes based on your class, and several
initial training sessions.  You can increase your attributes by
using these sessions at a trainer (there are several in town).

It takes one training session to improve an attribute, or to increase
mana or hp by 10. You recieve only one (1) session per every 5 levels.

The best attributes to train first are WIS and CON.  WIS gives you more
practice when you gain a level.  CON gives you more hit points.
In the long run, your character will be most powerful if you train
WIS and CON both to 18 before practising or training anything else.
~

102 TRUST~
Syntax: trust <character> <level>

TRUST sets a character's trust to the specified level.  This is similar to
advancing the character for accessing immortal commands, but has no effect
on combat strength, et cetera.  You can give more trust to mortal (or
immortal) characters to give them access to more power without messing up
the character.  You can also restrict a player's trust to less than their
natural level.

A trust of 0 means to use the character's natural level again.
~

102 ALLOW BAN PERMBAN~
Syntax: allow   <site>
	ban     <site> <newbies|all|permit>
	ban

BAN <site> prohibits players from that site from logging in.  BAN with
no arguments lists the banned sites.  ALLOW <site> removes a site from
the ban list, if the remover is of equal or higher level than the banner.

A site may have all players, new players, or non-permitted players (set
by editing the player file) banned, by changing the argument after the site.
*s may be used to ban either by suffix (*.edu), prefix (labmac*), or 
content (*andrews*), but be careful not to accidently lock out too many
sites with a wildcard.  Bans do not save unless the permban command is used.
~

102 REBOOT SHUTDOWN~
Syntax: reboot
	shutdown

Reboot shuts down the server.  When the normal 'startup' script is used
to control the server, a delay of fifteen seconds will ensue (to allow
old connections to die), followed by a reboot.

Shutdown shuts down the server and prevents the normal 'startup' script
from restarting it.
~

102 WIZLOCK NEWLOCK~
Syntax: wizlock
	newlock

Wizlock and newlock both block login attempts to ROM. Wizlock locks
out all non-gods (i.e. level less than 102), except for link-dead players
who are returning. Newlock only locks out new character generation,
typically used for preventing a spammer from returning. Wizlocking should be
avoided if at all possible, and newlocking should be accomponied by mail
or a note to the Imps.

A god must be at least Supreme level to wizlock the game.
~

102 DENY~
Syntax: deny <name>

Deny locks a character out of a game permanently, rendering their character
name unusable.  It may only be removed by editing the file, for this reason
freeze is usually preferred.
~

102 DISCONNECT~
Syntax: disconnect <name>

Disconnect breaks a player's link to the game, dumping them back to the telnet
prompt.  This is a non-lethal way of getting rid of spammers and annoying
players.
~

102 FREEZE~
Syntax: freeze <name>

FREEZE <character> is a toggle which prevents a character from issuing any
commands at all. It can be removed from within the game, so freezing a 
troublemaker is usually a better option than they deny command.
~

102 SOCKETS~
Syntax: sockets
	sockets <name> 

SOCKETS reports all of the visible users connected to the server, including 
users in the process of logging in.  The two numbers inside brackets are the 
channel number and the 'connected' state.  The 'connected' states are listed in 
merc.h: 0 is CON_PLAYING; non-zero values are various states of logging in.

The optional name argument shows the site of a player, or optional can be used
to identify switched gods (i.e. socket orc shows the name of anyone switched
into an orc).
~

102 LOAD~
Syntax: load mob <vnum>
	load obj <vnum> <level>

The load command is used to load new objects or mobiles (use clone to 
duplicate strung items and mobs).  The vnums can be found with the vnum
command, or by stat'ing an existing mob or object.

Load puts objects in inventory if they can be carried, otherwise they are
put in the room.  Mobiles are always put into the same room as the god. Old
format objects must be given a level argument to determine their power, new
format objects have a preset level that cannot be changed without set.
(see also clone, vnum, stat)
~

102 SET~
Syntax: set mob   <mobile> <field> <value>
	set obj   <object> <field> <value>
	set room  <number> <field> <value>
	set skill <char>   <name>  <rating>
	set skill <char>   all     <rating>

The set command is used to change the numerical values of the various data
structures. Type set <class> without an argument to see a listing of options.
Set skill all (pc's only) will set all the character's skills to the value
given.  Use string to change the strings on an object or mobile.
(see also string, stat)
~

102 STRING~
Syntax:
{x  string char <name> <field> <string>
{x    fields: name short long desc title spec racetext
{x  string obj  <name> <field> <string>
{x    fields: name short long extended

The string command changes the various strings associated with an object or
mobile.  A full list of fields can be viewed by typing string obj or string
mob.  Sorry, multi-line strings are not yet supported.
~

102 NOCHANNEL NOEMOTE NOSHOUT NOTELL~
Syntax: nochannel <character>
	noemote   <character>
	noshout   <character>
	notell    <character>

Noemote, noshout, and notell are used to muffle other characters, by
preventing them from emoting, shouting, and telling, respectively.
Characters who are noshout'ed or no'telled will also not receive those
forms of communication.

There are no open public channels here at Legends of Krynn, nor is shouting
a channel anymore. They already have YELL, no need to have a SHOUT command
too. So, there really is no point in using the NOCHANNEL or NOSHOUT commands.
 
The NOEMOTE and NOTELL commands are still pretty effective, but unless the
person is harrasing another player constantly and out of Roleplay, there is
no real need to ever use them.
~

1 PARDON~
Syntax: Pardon <character> <killer|thief|assault|treason|outlaw>
 
Pardon dismisses the charges (the flag they have) from a player. Pardoning
someone should be used ONLY if they deserve it and/or can be found innocent.
Keep in mind, with Solamnics being the only ones who can CHARGE and PARDON
a person, pardoning someone who was charged by someone else, means that your
overruling their decision, which could cause hate, discontent and chaos
among the Clan. Another valid reason to dismiss someone is if the accuser
who wanted charges to be brought up, decides to change his or her mind
and wants to have them dismissed. Or, if a person serves a sentence in
jail or is administered some other form of punishment, then they can be
dismissed as well.
~

102 PURGE~
Syntax: purge
	purge <character>

Purge is used to clean up the world.  Purge with no arguments removes all the
NPC's and objects in the current room.  Purge with an argument purges one
character from anywhere in the world.

Purge will not get rid of PC's, or objects or mobiles with a NOPURGE flag
set (i.e. the pit, the fountain, shopkeepers, Hassan).  Mobiles may be
purged if they are called directly by name.
~

102 PLOAD PUNLOAD~
Syntax: PLOAD <character's name>
{x        PUNLOAD <character's name>

Use pload to load characters into the current location.
Use punload for sending the characters back into reality. 
Characters are loaded into a link dead (LD) state.
You cannot pload or punload characters that are currently in the game.
~

102 for~
FOR ALL <action>
FOR MORTALS <action>
FOR GODS <action>
FOR <level> <action>
FOR MOBS <action>
FOR EVERYWHERE <action>

Executes action several times, either on 

ALL players (not including yourself),

MORTALS (including trusted characters), 

GODS (characters with level higher than 102), 

<LEVEL> those who are AT or ABOVE the level you specify (can not enter
{x        a value below 1, nor exceed level 110)

MOBS (NEVER USE) or 

every room (NEVER USE EITHER!)

If you insert a # in the action, it will be replaced by the name of the
target.
If # is a part of the action, the action will be executed for every target
in game. If there is no #, the action will be executed for every room
containg
at least one target, but only once per room. # cannot be used with FOR
EVERY-
WHERE. # can be anywhere in the action.
Example: 
FOR ALL SMILE -> you will only smile once in a room with 2 players.
FOR ALL TWIDDLE # -> In a room with A and B, you will twiddle A then B.
[Hit Return to continue]
Destroying the characters this command acts upon MAY cause it to fail. Try
to
avoid something like FOR MOBS PURGE (although it actually works at my
MUD).
FOR MOBS TRANS 3054 (transfer ALL the mobs to Midgaard temple) does NOT
work
though :)
The command works by transporting the character to each of the rooms with 
target in them. Private rooms are not violated.
~

