1 'TRUEFIRE'~
Syntax: c 'truefire'
 
This spell creates a magical fire which, when held, gives
a person protection from evil and bonuses to their hit and
damage rolls. The bonuses vary with level.
~

102 PREFIX~
Syntax: prefix <command>
 
This nifty command comes in handy when you need to use a Command more than
once in a row, and you don't want to keep typing the command out. How this
works is:
 
If you want to use the TELL command, and even more specifically, you want to
send a TELL to a guy named GEORGE, but you don't want to have to keep
typing TELL GEORGE before what you want to say.
~

1 'PHANTOM ARMOR'~
Syntax: c 'phantom armor'

When this spell is cast, the wizard creates a quasi-real suit of plate
mail.  This semi-illusory material covers the subject and actually gives
some real protection.  This spell will not function with most other magical
protections, like Sanctuary, Armor, and Shield.  This also applies to those
other spells, as they will not work when affected by this spell.  The
protection provided is quite substantial.  
~

102 'PPRESTART'~
Syntax: pprestart
 
This command restarts up the Player Port <ONLY> when the PP is down. The
PROCESS MUST be already dead in order for this to work. If not, you won't
be able to boot up CSH for it. This command may ONLY be used on the BP, or
Builder Port. This is helpful when someone can not access the SHELL from
wherever they are logging on from. This command utilizes the core SHELL,
so do not overdo it.
~

102 'PLIST'~
Syntax: Plist <all>
        Plist <immortal>
 
This command displays a complete list of either ALL the players, including
Immortals, OR just Immortals. Along with this list, next to each name is
the number of days since that person last logged on <pfile has been modified>
 
The days are set in color. Anything that's 10 days or less, is in {gGreen{x.
From 11 to 20 days, the color is in {yYellow{x. And, anyone with days which
exceed 20, are marked in {rRed{x.
 
This command can function also as a good way to read through Pfiles, checking
on names of players. This can be used for seeing which ones
need to be deleted/denied,etc.
 
~

102 'DISABLE'~
Syntax: Disable
{x        Disable <command name>
 
This command disables commands. It will NOT disable SPELLS, of course, you
could disable the entire CAST command, which would end up disabling every
spell in the game: DON'T DO IT. This helps when there's a command which is
BUGGY, or thought to be BUGGED. This will prevent anyone, including all Imms
from being able to use it. Don't abuse this, and if a command is disabled
by someone else other than you, do NOT enable the command unless you know
for sure it's been fixed.
 
To re-enable a command that's on this list, simply type DISABLE <command>.
Disabling a command which has already been disabled, will in fact, enable the
command. So be careful not to accidentally disable something and forget to
re-disable it again so it's back on the disable list. Typing in this command
without any argument, will show you a list of commands currently on the
DISABLE LIST. Next to each disabled command, will be the LEVEL at which
the command was disabled and the name of the person who disabled it. The
LEVEL, means that anyone who's NOT of the same level or HIGHER, can not
enable the command. So if it's level 110, that means only the Imps can
enable the command.
~

102 'ILLEGALNAME'~
Syntax: Illegalname <name>
 
This command adds a player name to a list which means that it will no longer
be able to be used for character creation. Any name on this list can not
be used to create a character. This way, we don't have to HARD CODE every
name we find unsuitable for usage. Don't worry, this command is dummified,
so that you can not add the same name twice. If a name is accidentally
added to this list that needs to be removed, please see an administrator
for help.
~

102 'CLEAN'~
Syntax: clean old
        clean deny
        clean size
        clean all
 
This command cleans Pfiles. It WILL create game lag, so be careful as to
when you use this command. It's prefered that you wait till a time when there
aren't so many players on.
 
CLEAN ALL is about the only one that's really need to be used. It reads
through every Pfile and deletes all those that either have DENY flags (set
when a player is denied), and/or Pfiles which have been inactive for around
3 to 4 months. This command will also show you a list of names of Pfiles
that are extremely large. The players of those Pfiles should be notified
to drop some of their Inventory, because they're carrying too much. Large
Pfiles create game lag, and also can corrupt Pfiles, due to saving problems.
Looking at the other arguments, it's pretty easy to figure out
what each one does. CLEAN DENY only purges pfiles with a DENY flag set.
CLEAN OLD, only purges Pfiles that have been inactive for 3 to 4 months. And
CLEAN SIZE only shows Pfiles which are eating up large amounts of memory.
~

102 'VIOLATE'~
Syntax: violate <VNUM/player name>
 
This command functions like GOTO. Only this command overrides the PRIVATE
flags that may be set on a room. If a room isn't private, and GOTO could
be used, this command will not work and will refer you to use the GOTO
command instead.
~

102 'APURGE'~
Syntax: Apurge
        Apurge <player>
 
This command will completely purge a player of ALL AFFECTS that
they may have. With NO Argument added, it will purge you, yourself.
There are 0 restrictions or any exceptions. It completely removes
ALL AFFECTS from that person. Be careful when using this though. Do
NOT abuse it. Purging someone who has tons of beneficial affects,
may wind up pissing them off, possibley making them want to quit, or
worse.
~

102 'FLAG'~
Syntax: flag mob  <name> <field> <flags>
{x        flag char <name> <field> <flags>
{x        mob  flags: act,aff,off,imm,res,vuln,form,part
{x        char flags: aff2,plr,comm,aff,imm,res,vuln,aff3
{x        +: add flag, -: remove flag, = set equal to
{x        otherwise flag toggles the flags listed.
 
If all that up there confuses you, do NOT even bother to use this command at
all. This command changes FLAGS set on players and NPCs alike. The list of
flag fields is listed above. For each field, it's up to you to know or figure
out which flag needs to be changed in that field. For example, using:
 
FLAG HIDDUKEL COMM NOPRAY
 
That command would change his Pfile so that in the COMM portion, the NOPRAY
flag would be set, which means he would be able to use the PRAY command. Now,
typing in that exact same command, toggles the flag, removing the NOPRAY
flag from his COMM field, which means he'd be able to use the PRAY command
once again. This command may be very confusing for most, so don't use it
if you don't know what your doing. You could end up screwing up someone's
Pfile, or an NPC.
~

1 'EYERUB'~
Syntax: eyerub
 
This skill allows a person to rub their eyes and have a 75% chance of
successfully rubbing out either SMOKE or DIRT from their eyes, allowing
them to once again, see, without having to wait for the affects to wear off
naturally. Be warned, if failure results, rubbing one's eyes will only make
matters worse, worsening the affects of blindness from Flaming Smoke and
Dirt.
~

1 'SPOOK'~
Syntax: c 'spook' <target>
 
This spell works very similar to the Fear spell Necromancers have, only
this spell allows an Illusionist to create a very frightening illusion, which
scares the living bejesus out of their victim, causing them to flee.
~

1 'FINGERBREAK' 'FINGER BREAK'~
Syntax: fingerbreak
 
This skill allows fighters to smash their victim's fingers, which reduces
their victim's ability to hit them as often with a wielded weapon. This
will also render a Mage from being able to cast any spells, since a mage
relys heavily on channeling their magic through their hands and fingers.
Broken fingers prevent magic from being properly channeled, hence it makes
a mage powerless with their magic. There's a catch to this, and that is that
both, the fighter and the victim must both be fighting each other, and both
must be in the front rank of their groups.
~

1 'EXECUTE'~
Syntax: Execute <victim>
 
This skill allows a warrior skilled with an axe, to execute someone, lobbing
off their head. The victim must be unconcious in order for this to work, and
the executioner must not be in any type of combat. This skill only works 30%
of the time. The executioner must also be wielding an Axe in order for this
to work. No axe, no execution.
~

1 'EARPUNCH'~
Syntax: earpunch
 
This skill allows a fighter to, using their bare hands, punch their victims
in the ears with a clapping motion. This will deafen their victims and put
them into dizzy state of mind. Both, the fighter and the victim must be in
the front ranks of their group, and the fighter can not execute this while
wielding a weapon. There is a 25 percent chance that a magic user will fail
in casting spells when in this state.
~

1 'BRAINJAR'~
Syntax: brainjar <victim>
 
Striking a very hard blow to the head, this skill renders a victim incoherent.
They will be so dizzy, walking will be quite difficult, and even their speech
is affected. Victims will fall down trying to walk around as well, just as if
they were drunk. This skill can not be performed while in battle, and both
the Barbarian and the victim must be in the front rows of their ranks. If
the attempted blow to the head fails, an attack is initiated. However,
if it is a success, no attack is initiated at all, and the victim walks
around incoherently.
~

1 'DEVOTE' 'DEVOTION'~
Syntax: devote <God/Goddess>

If you have decided to follow a certain God or Goddess, you may go to
his/her temple and devote yourself to them.  By devoting yourself to your
God or Goddess, you are showing that you are truly committed to following
that diety's tenets.  This does by any means, bind you to that God or
Goddess for eternity.  It is quite possible to devote yourself to a
different God or Goddess, if you should change your mind (Roleplay ONLY). 
Once you have devoted yourself, you are marked with a small token of
devotion.  This token merely represents that you have devoted yourself to a
certain God or Goddess.  If certain devotional tasks or quests are fulfilled
(through RP ONLY, and depending upon the god), it is possible to receive the
True Mark of that God or Goddess.  True Marks are an actual representation
to whom you devote your entire life to, and to whom you shall be forever
devoted to, no matter what happens.  To be stripped of this mark, is to cast
shame and bad luck down upon you.  Being stripped of your True Mark will
also prevent future marking from being easy.  
 
The helpfile for each god lists a reference at the bottom, which one
may use to receive more information on their religion.
~

1 'RUPTURE ORGAN'~
Syntax: rupture organ
 
This skill allows a Barbarian who's proficient in Hand to Hand combat to get
in a deadly blow to their victim's organs. There is only a slight chance (10%)
that the blow will actually rupture enough organs to kill the victim on the
spot. Any other blow usually results in slightly ruptured organs, which
result in internal bleeding for the poor victim. Internal bleeding
will slowly injure a person, inflicting damage over time, at least until
the bleeding stops. This skill will not work while wielding
a weapon. The Barbarian must also be at least 95% proficient in Hand to Hand
combat. Proficiency in THIS skill, will not determine whether the blow is
fatal or not, but if the blow is not fatal, then skill proficiency will
determine whether or not the victim is even hit hard enough to do any
damage at all.
~

1 'KNOWLEDGE' 'KNOWLEDGE RELIGION'~
The followers of Knowledge value information and learning above all else.
Those who choose to follow this path dedicate their lives not only to
learning all they can in every aspect of their lives, but to sharing that
knowledge with others who seek enlightenment.  However, Gilean also upholds
the right of mortals to choose their own destinies - he does not condone
those who attempt to "force" their knowledge upon others, instead
considering such an act to be an abuse of the Balance.
 
Followers of Gilean are encouraged to serve as teachers, historians
and mediators. They owe allegiance to neither Good nor Evil;
believing that Knowledge in its pure form knows no such distinctions.
As such, they are forbidden to use their knowledge to sway others
to either side. Gilean's followers realize that truth is often
elusive and beliefs may change; therefore they do not seek to judge,
instead preferring to serve as impartial observers and objective
mediators.
 
Persons wishing to devote themselves to Gilean may be of any
ethos, but MUST be of Neutral alignment; those who stray too far from this
path may soon find themselves stripped of their religion if Gilean feels
that their objectivity has been compromised. Class and/or race
restrictions are the same as those listed in HELP BALANCE ORDER.
 
For further detail about expectations and duties, please see
HELP KNOWLEDGE2
~

