1 'ROLEPLAYING ETHICS' 'PLAYERKILLING ETHICS'~
The words ROLEPLAYING and PKING were used together as this help file
includes both, together as a whole, rather than just one of them
separately.
 
If you haven't read the help files on PLAYERKILLING and ROLEPLAYING, then
do so now. Make sure to read the WHOLE thing for each of them, and
understand them to the best of your ability. Now, onto Player Killing and
the Roleplay involved/required leading up to that point. In the HELP PK
file, it clearly states that one must have a motive for killing another
player. They must also be able to explain themselves (This means to an
Immortal if questioned, OR a Solamnic Knight if it involves being charged
with a crime).
 
Some of the BIGGEST Myths and Misconceptions about PKing include:
 
  ** #1 - You must Roleplay your motives/reasons for why your going to PK
     someone PRIOR to actually attacking them, through SAY's or other In
     Character means of communication.
 
- This is completely wrong! Your motives do NOT need to be justified by
telling the soon-to-be-victim WHY you're going to PK them through IC
channels. It is totally acceptable to walk up and PK a person without
giving any heads-up at all. Notifying someone what you're GOING to do
only gives them a head start to either get away, log off, or call for some
backup, which would all be (more or less) Out Of Character reactions.

Now, there ARE stipulations to this and they include, but are not limited to:
 
  a) You can't just log on, and go PK someone within a few heartbeats of
having logged on. This would be obvious to show there's no way you had
any RP merit to kill that person (unless of course, something took place
during a previous login that was not yet settled).
 
  b) You can't just walk up to characters you've NEVER even met before in
the GAME. Even *IF* you know it's someone's ALT, you still haven't met
that character in the game, IN CHARACTER, hence, your character doesn't
really KNOW that character at all.
 
  c) You attack someone and/or their ALTS because you don't like them
OOCly. This is one of the BIGGEST no-no's in the game, and will result in
an instant loss (Denial) of your character.

  d) You can't attack them more than ONCE in a 24 hour REAL LIFE time
period. As it states in HELP PK, it's only justifiable to kill them more
than once IF and ONLY IF, they seek retribution by trying to attack you,
yet you win.
 
  e) The player is obviously a Newbie. Attacking newbies, especially those
who don't even know what in the hell is going on as far as your entire
Roleplay storyline will result in your character ALSO being denied.
 
  ** #2 - You've killed a player but aren't allowed to do anything to or with their EQ.
 
- You can do anything you want to their corpse. Feel free to loot, burn,
pillage, sodomize, or anything you feel is just and IN Character to their
corpse.
 
Folks, you can PK for whatever reasons you want, just make sure it can be
justified if you are ever questioned by an Immortal. If you get PK'd by
someone, and don't feel that it was for any Roleplay reason whatsoever,
try talking to that person, the one who attacked you, through TELLS or any
other means available to you. If that person is unresponsive, and you
can't think of any other way to get even on your own, send a NOTE to
Immortal, with a brief LOG of what took place if you can. PK's are going
to happen, learn to deal with them without looking for an Immortal crutch.

If it gets out of hand (And we can see logs of every PK attempt/success
that takes place), we will step in and deal harsh punishments. If, however,
everyone starts whining about a PK attempt/success regardless of the
reasons, it will start turning this MUD into a Political MUD, with players
and staff alike, debating over the logic of what happened, what should
have happened, and who should receive disciplinary action. That's not fun
for anyone, and our goal here is to entertain, not to babysit or to start
resorting to Political Debates.
~

1 'ENFORCING ROLEPLAY' 'ENFORCING RP' 'ENFORCE RP' 'ENFORCE ROLEPLAYING'~
This HELP file is available to ALL players and staff alike, to read,
although it is here to serve more as a guideline of expectations of the
Immortal Staff Staff when it comes to enforcing Roleplay, and gives the
Players an idea of what we look for and what we do when it comes to
enforcing Roleplay.  
 
Lets start with the very basics, since the biggest misconceptions of enforcing
roleplay comes from the meaning of the words. We an Enforced Roleplaying MUD. This
means that we ENFORCE Roleplay when deemed neccissary. However, we do not FORCE
Roleplay, or at least should NOT be forcing RP. There's a BIG difference between
those two. The best analogy that could be given so people can have a better
understanding of the difference between the two, would be to use our great Police
Enforcement Agencies, or Public Safety, depending on where you live, as an example.
Their JOB is to ENFORCE the LAW, however, as most of you can testify either
by personal experience or by other means, Police like to FORCE the law onto people,
rather than protect us and ENFORCE the law. For example, when it comes to having
paraphernalia in an automobile, it is against the law and it is up to the Police
to enforce that law, by such means as handing punishing those who fail to uphold
to that law by say, getting caught with a gigantic water bong sitting in the front
seat when the person gets pulled over for a different traffic violation. However,
when a Policeman pulls someone over and can't see any Paraphernalia in plain view,
but for whatever reason, decides he wants to do an illegal search of the car without
concent or a warrent, and only by this, FINDS something, that is no longer considered
to be ENFORCING the LAW, but now that Policeman is FORCING the LAW. If you still
can't see the difference, many other examples can be given. Police HARRASSING
citizens by doing things like tailing you when your driving, etc., or profiling
you because of the way you look, dress, smell, act, etc. is no longer ENFORCING
the law, but now FORCING the LAW.
 
We do NOT want that here at all. Immortal Staff members are expected to ENFORCE
Roleplay, which does NOT mean that you POOF into a room with a player, or switch
into a MOB that's in the same room as a player, then try Roleplaying with the
player and if the player decides to ignore it, or decides that he/she doesn't want
to Roleplay the situation the Immortal is presenting, to severely PUNISH that
player. Punishing a player for non-roleplaying antics should ONLY be dealt out
in situations like when a player outright makes it a point to be against the MUD's
Roleplaying enviroment by making statements out of character to other players.
Another situation could be if a player purposely sabotages other people's RP. For
example, if Bob and Jim are Roleplaying at a temple, and Frank walks into the
room and starts making fun of their Roleplay, or starts Roleplaying really
idiotic with intensions of ruining Bob and Jim's Roleplay, then a severe RP
punishment would be justifiable. Punishments should be dealt with by deducting
Experience Points from said person. In no way should an Immortal start casting
offensive spells, or chasing after to kill the person, or start harrassing the
player, or anything of the like. We are professionals and should act like it. We
are NOT to lower ourselves by seeking retribution through childish means against
a player for bad RP.
 
Enforcing Roleplay also includes setting GOOD examples to the players. This doesn't
mean snooping people, seeing that they keep using OOC content in IC channels, then
poofing to them and start throwing a hissy fit by yelling at them and telling them
that they aren't suppose to do that. Be tactful and lead by example. Tactfully
tell them that using OOC content in IC channels is wrong. Notify them of which
channels are IC and which ones are OOC if they do not know. Give them examples of
what would be good IC content and what would be not. If they are treated in this
manner, they will be more likely to try harder at Roleplaying and less likely to
hold a grudge against that Immortal and/or start hostile name-calling. Treat every
player with respect, and you shall be respected back.
 
We are a Roleplay Enforced MUD, we are NOT an RPI (Role Play Intensive) MUD. The
difference is, that an RPI MUD is about as close to a MUSH as you can get, without
actually being a MUSH. RPI MUD's are extreme, and hardly have any actual Game Play.
Roleplay Enforced means that we will help to enforce Roleplay, but hey, if a player
decides one day that all he wants to do is be alone, or with a buddy of his, and
just wants to go around and kill for Experience Points, then so be it, leave them
alone. As long as they are having FUN, that is what is most important. We will
NEVER bend this MUD to accept only a certain group of individuals. In other words,
this MUD will NOT be a MUD that is only FUN to the Hack 'n' Slash players, NOR will
it ever be a MUD that is only FUN for the Serious Roleplay Adventurers. We want to
maintain a good equal balance of fun and entertainment for both types of people,
or at least we need to try. If they aren't having FUN because of the actions of a
certain Immortal, then you aren't doing your job correctly and need to readjust
your ways of thinking.
~

1 'TAME'~
Syntax: tame <victim>
 
This skill allows a skilled Ranger or Druid to be able to tame animals out in the
wild. This can only be done on Animals. Anything else will result in failure and
even the possibility of upsetting the non-animal, provoking them to attack. This
skill can only be used out in the wild. It will not work on animals in cities
and places of the like.
~

1 'ENTANGLE'~
Syntax: cast 'entangle' <victim>
 
This spell can only be used by the Masters of Nature, the Druids. By using this
spell, the caster calls forth Vines from his or her surroundings, which then
tightly grip around their victim's legs, immobilizing them. This spell can only
be cast in particular locations, such as Forest, Mountains, Hills, Fields, and it
can even be cast underwater, calling forth the water vines deep in the seas.
~

1 'WISDOM OF MAJERE'~
Followers of Majere embrace the goal of Wisdom through strict
self-discipline and meditation. While many who follow Majere go out into
the world to teach the ways of enlightenment and counter the lies and
temptations of evil, all receive their initial training through monasteries.
Though Majere's following is small, his clerics are among the most
influential on Krynn, and comprise some of the greatest theologians and
teachers throughout history.

Followers of Wisdom adhere to a strict monastic lifestyle, taking vows
of poverty, obedience, and chastity in order to focus on achieving
enlightenment and holiness through the denial of worldly temptations.
Those who follow this lifestyle tend to prefer unarmed forms of martial
arts - many in order to learn physical and spiritual control, others in an
effort to both receive and spread spiritual enlightenment; preferring to
focus on clarifying and understanding the doctrines of the deities of
Good.
 
Followers of Wisdom are most often of Lawful ethos, Good alignment, or
both. Those of Chaotic ethos typically find the rigid discipline of
monastic life too limiting and seek out other, less restrictive ways of
serving the cause of Good.
 
Those wishing to receive the Mark of true enlightenment must often spend
hours, days, or even weeks in a state of fasting, meditation and prayer.
If the follower shows remarkable focus and discipline, Majere himself
will occasionally grant a puzzle or task through which the seeker may
attain a fraction of the god's wisdom.
 
All who embrace the path to Wisdom are guided by the following tenets:
 
  ** Seek holiness both by overcoming the Evil within and opening
     yourself to Good.
  ** Discipline the unruly passions of the body, and look within to find
     your own faults and strengths.
  ** Seek not glory or perishable things, but the eternal joy of light
  ** Obey those properly set above you, and be gentle but firm to those
     below
  ** Help call others to virtue through teaching and example, not force
     and fear
  ** Oppose evil with fervor, but without hatred
  ** Show mercy when possible, but be hard when necessary
~

1 'GUARDIANS' 'GUARDS'~
Each clan has guards or guardians placed throughout the clan's base of
operations.  These mobs can not be charmed, summoned, nor can they move. 
However, these guards or guardians will protect the Clan Hall from outsiders
(Anyone not in the perspective clan).  Each Clan Member has the ability to
control these guardians in three (3) ways.  They can make them Go on Alert,
Go on Duty, or Go off Duty.  To do this, you must be first in the same room
as the guardian.  Then, using the SAY channel, you can SAY one of the
following three things: 
 
go on alert
 
go on duty
 
go off duty
 
Now, each one of these will put the Guardian into a different mode of protection.
Each one will be described here.
 
* Go On Alert - This command makes the Guardian become fully alert. This means that
                chances are, they will attack anyone who tries to enter the clan
                and yet does NOT belong to that clan. The only way around this for
                the player being attacked, is to outright KILL them.
 
* Go On Duty  - This state of protection, makes the Guardian be more attentive as
                to who comes into the Clan Hall. They do NOT attack people, but will
                rather show them the way out (to the front entrance of the Clan)
                if they do not belong in the clan. There IS a 40 percent chance that
                the Guardians will only notice the player AFTER they have moved to
                the next room, which means they won't stop the player, but, the
                Guardians WILL send a Clan Tell to all fellow clan members as to WHO
                has entered the Clan.
 
* Go Off Duty - This command will make the Guardian become more relaxed in his 
                duties. He will allows anyone, in or out of the clan, into the Clan
                Hall.
 
Now, it should be noted that when you USE these commands on a Guard or Guardian,
that it will *ONLY* affect the Guard or Guardian in the room with you that you are
giving orders to. It will *NOT* affect the rest of the Guards or Guardians that
are in the rest of the Clan Hall. Each one must be individually set. It should
also be noted that if a Copyover or Reboot of the MUD takes place, ALL Guards or
Guardians WILL revert to a default state, which is the same as the Go On Duty
command. These Guards or Guardians CAN be killed. They are not meant to keep ALL
players out 100 percent of the time. They are of higher level, so it is not highly
recommended to go charge in a clan not of your own, and start trying to raise hell
with the Guards or Guardians by killing them, if your of a significant lower level.
~

1 'HEROIC DEMISE'~
This skill is automatic.  It does not require any input by the player,
just requires that the player have the skill.  When the player who has this
skill dies, there is a chance that he or she will be able to deal a good
amount of damage to their foe, right before dying.  When the player has been
struck the last fatal blow or spell, he or she pulls out a dagger and lunges
it into their foe, which will leave them with only one-tenth of their total
hit points left.  If the foe of the soon-to-be-dead in a second, already has
less than that amount already, nothing happens.  
~

1 'ENDURE DISEASE'~
Syntax: cast 'endure disease'
 
This spell will produce a misty green cloud of smoke, which will then
circle around the caster, then enter the caster's body through any and all open
orifices, mouth, nose, skin pores, etc.. This spell gives the caster endurance
against disease type spells. Those type of spells include, but not limited to,
Plague, Poison, and Gas Breath. In the case of Gas Breath, the damage is still
done, however the chances of being affected by the spell's side affect, being
poisoned, are greatly reduced. This spell reduces these affects by 65 percent. So,
any of these spells cast on the affected person, only have a 35 percent chance of
success.
~

0 'CHIVALRY' 'CHIVALRY RELIGION'~
While Habbakuk tends to be followed by rangers, sailors, farmers or
anyone else with strong ties to the bounty of land and sea, the actual
clergy is divided between clerics and druids.  Clerics of Habbakuk have no
central authority to which they answer, nor are they strictly organized. 
Instead, the followers of the Fisher King serve to protect nature from those
who would destroy or squander it.  
 
Followers typically serve their communities by looking after herd animals,
protecting the community from animal attacks, planting saplings, guarding
against forest fires and assisting those who show respect for nature. Clerics
of Habbakuk may also be found working alongside healers of Mishakal.
 
Followers of Habbakuk tend to be of any ethos, though always of Good
alignment. Once during their lifetime, followers must leave friends and
family to wander the land; taking nothing but a walking stick and the
clothes on their back. This 'wandering period' serves to purify the
follower and help them to learn the true ways of nature and their god.
The wandering ends when the follower has either performed a service for
their god or Habbakuk send the follower a sign.
 
Those who would follow Habbakuk are charged to live by the following:
 
  ** Live in harmony with nature and respect all living things

  ** Treat animals well, for they are a gift from the gods

  ** Those who seek to spoil or squander the land are the enemy

  ** Be prepared to fight in defense of the land and the creatures in
     your care
~

0 'JUSTICE' 'JUSTICE RELIGION'~
The followers of Kiri-Jolith serve Justice by seeking out evil and
tyranny in all of its forms in order to wage war against them.  Whether
defending their communities from hostile incursions, or liberating those
under the weight of oppression, followers of Justice are among the most
active in the fight against those who serve darkness.  

Those worshipping the god of righteous warfare tend to be mainly
comprised of knights, warriors and battle-clerics. Clerics of
Kiri-Jolith train daily and diligently to be prepared in the never ending
fight against Evil. Wherever they serve, these clerics are organized
with military precision, and each knows their place within the ranks.
Followers of Justice speak often of their faith, inspiring others with
their courage and honor. Most devout followers of Kiri-Jolith join the
ranks of the Solamnic Knights, seeking their place within the Order of
the Sword.
 
Followers of Justice are most often of Lawful ethos, Good alignment, or
both. Those of Chaotic ethos typically find the military discipline of
Kiri-Jolith too restrictive and seek out other, less regimented ways of
serving the cause of Good.
 
Those wishing to be Mark'ed by their god must typically perform some
great deed involving righting some unjust action and/or helping those in
great need. All who follow the ways of Justice adhere to the following
principles:

  ** Good is its own reward

  ** Honor and courage are life - Cowardice is to be reviled

  ** Never refuse to fight for a cause that is just

  ** Never retreat while an evil opponent remains on the battlefield
~

