0 'BLESSING' 'BLESSING RELIGION'~
The followers of Mishakal are among the most numerous and active of the
priesthoods throughout Krynn, actively helping those in need and promoting
the Blessing of their goddess wherever they can.  Instrumental in bringing
about the word of the gods during the War of the Lance, they work tirelessly
to bring peace and comfort among the troubled people of Krynn.  
 
Clerics of Mishakal are required by their goddess to heal anyone who asks,
regardless of alignment. While some may charge for their services (sometimes
quite expensively for those who are evil), Mishakal forbids her clerics from
withholding their services from those who cannot afford it. In addition,
clerics of Mishakal often officiate at significant events such as births,
deaths and marriages; blessing newborns, offering comfort and last rites
to the dying, and consecrating vows.
 
All followers of Mishakal must work toward the good of the community in
which they live, and often travel extensively.  Followers may be of any
ethos, but MUST be of Good alignment. Those wishing to receive the full
Blessing of Mishakal must strive constantly to heal the ills of those around
them and minister to all creatures. This may often involve actively working
against the disease and decay spread by Morgion and his worshippers.
 
Those who would devote their lives to the Blue Lady's Blessing must adhere
to the following, set forth in the legendary Disks of Mishakal:

  ** Heal all who require it, be they friend or foe
  ** Drive out disease and decay and bring light to those who live in
     darkness and ignorance
  ** Promote peace and harmony and lend help to those who cannot help
     themselves
  ** Do not raise weapons in anger, but defend yourself and those whose
     lives are in danger
  ** Honor those who have passed on, but remember that your duties lie with
     those who are left behind
~

0 'VIRTUE' 'VIRTUE RELIGION'~
The followers of Virtue devote their lives to championing the deities of
Good; leading by example and encouragement, rather than restriction. 
Concerned chiefly with the welfare of all the peoples of Krynn, they serve
to aid Paladine in the defense of his beloved creation against Evil.  
 
Devotees of the Master of Law, the followers of Virtue believe that a
government that is good and just is necessary for a free and stable
society. As such, they often work side by side with the rulers of the
regions they inhabit, serving their communities as judges, advisors,
counselors and law enforcement officials.
 
Clerics of Paladine focus on providing spiritual guidance to the people.
While the clergy of Mishakal tend to the healing of the body, the Revered
Sons and Daughters of Paladine tend to the healing of the spirit; helping
the weak and defenseless, counseling the common folk on matters of faith,
and providing shelter to those they feel are wrongly accused.
 
As Paladine is the Father of Good and Master of Law, his followers tend to
be of Lawful ethos and Good alignment without exception. While many devote
themselves in name, true blessings come only to those who embrace the
tenets of Virtue wholeheartedly. Paladine's favor is generally bestowed
upon those who, by their dedication and example, lead others to dedicate
their lives to the cause of Good.
 
All those who would live in Virtue live by the following code:
 
  ** The guilty must be brought before the law
  ** Good stands in contrast to Evil - neither can exist without the other
  ** Good redeems its own
  ** While the whole may be greater than the sum of its parts, each part
     is no less important. The greatest events in history are but a series
     of small moments.
  ** None are so lost that they cannot be brought to see the light
~

0 'NATURE RELIGION'~
The followers of Chislev embrace Nature in all its forms and defend the
wilderness against those who would do it harm.  Composed mainly of druids,
the church of Chislev welcomes all who would care for the natural world. 
Here and there, a few clerics may be found tending to small farming
communities or, in the case of elven societies, tending to the ancestral
forests surrounding their homeland.  
 
As the most devout of Nature's worshippers, druids of Chislev spend their
days traveling their protected areas, however large or small, and
correcting any imbalances they may find. Mornings are typically spent
healing animals and keeping watch for poachers or those setting snares or
traps unlawfully and without regard to the hazards of depopulation.
Afternoons are spent tending to the trees and plants of Chislev's domain.
Each spring, many of Chislev's clergy are welcomed by local communities
as they travel the land, blessing the crops in hopes of yielding a good
harvest. Many can be found working alongside those devoted to Habbakuk
to restore areas damaged by war, fire, or other unnatural causes.
 
Just as nature yields many creatures both dangerous and benign, followers
of Chislev come in many varieties. Devotees of Chislev may be of any
combination of ethos and alignment, so long as one or the other remains
Neutral. Those wishing to earn Chislev's favor must typically undertake
some quest involving the protection and/or restoration of an endangered
wilderness area, or combating those who would harm or corrupt it.
 
Followers of Chislev adhere to the following laws of Nature:
 
  ** The balance of nature must be maintained at all costs

  ** Nature should be protected and nurtured, not spoiled or enslaved

  ** There is a place for man-made things and innovation, but they should
     always come second to the true gift that is nature.
~

0 'REDMAGIC' 'RED MAGIC' 'REDMAGIC RELIGION' 'RED MAGIC RELIGION'~
The followers of Lunitari delicately tread the path of Neutrality, working
to balance Good and Evil, and often acting as the moderating voice of
reason and peace. While the forces of Good and Evil continue to vie for
control over the other, the forces of Neutrality seek only to maintain the
balance that keeps the world moving.
 
Lunitari has no clerical order, but rather is honored and respected as the
patron deity of the Red Robed order of the Conclave of High Sorcery. Her
followers are generally more numerous than those of Solinari or Nuitari,
and work to maintain the delicate balance that exists between good and
evil magic.
 
In keeping with the teachings and aims of Lunitari, all who would study
Red Magic may be of any combination of ethos and alignment, so long as one
or the other remains Neutral. Should a red-robed mage stray from these
beliefs, he or she may soon find themselves out of favor with their
goddess. Humans are by far the most prolific of Lunitari's followers,
though by no means exclusive. 
 
RESTRICTIONS: Certain races may be deemed unacceptable for the blessings
of Lunitari. These generally include: 

  ** Thaewar and Daergar: while dwarven wizards are not unheard of, these
     clans in particular are known for their tendency toward dark magic
  ** Gnomes: most gnomes exhibit a strong distaste for magic, preferring
     to rely on science and technology. While they may be capable of using
     magic, few realize they have the potential; indeed, calling a Gnome a
     wizard is considered by most to be a deadly insult.
  ** Kender: While kender are often very interested in the effects of
     magic, due to their inherent nature they are unable to maintain the
     necessary focus needed to master the magical arts.
  ** Draconians: the very existence of these creatures and the manner of
     their creation is an affront to the strictures of Neutrality.
  ** Elves: While red-robed elven wizards are not unheard of, elven
     society is so devoted to the gods of Good, that the practice of any
     but White magic is considered heresy and may well lead to the
     individual being branded a 'dark elf' and exiled from his or her
     homeland in shame. This is especially true among the Silvanesti.
 
Other races wishing to receive the blessings of Lunitari may do so at the
goddess' discretion. While recorded instances of sea elves, minotaurs and
others do exist, they are generally so few as to be considered aberrations.
 
Those followers wishing to receive a MARK of Lunitari's favor must often
undertake a quest of some sort involving the search for rare magical
artifacts, the use of magic to maintain the balance between the forces of
Good and Evil, or the gathering of "stray" mages into the fold. 
 
All mages MARK'ed by the goddess are asked to include themselves in the
Conclave of Wizards as a sign of solidarity and dedication to the Art.
Once accepted, Red mages are often the first choice for negotiators and
ambassadors of the Conclave, as well as dealing with Renegade wizards
Followers of Red Magic will attempt to bring their brethren before the
council, but will not hesitate to use force when reason fails.

The defining guidelines among followers of Red Magic are as follows:

  ** Devote yourself to Magic.
  ** Enhance and expand the use of magic in the world.
  ** Work to maintain the balance between Good and Evil magic
  ** Promote the use of Neutral magic, and bring other worthy candidates
     to the study of the Art.
~

